          • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

            Both goals were marginally offside, we're talking miniscule amounts which the naked eye almost certainly wouldn't pick up at speed, but we deserved to win and Spurs fans, to be fair to them, aren't really complaining. We played pretty much a perfect game although Kane looked stiff and that did help us. You are always going to concede some chances against Spurs but a lot of their efforts were speculative and we should've scored our first goal much earlier when Vertonghen went down under a meaty challenge from Oezil. Would've been a tap in for Lacazette and maybe even a bigger win margin. Mesut was unplayable and it was good to see our first choice XI on the field. Hopefully that continues and we can put a run together. Spurs shouldn't be too disheartened. They have players like Kane, Alli, Dembele, Winks who weren't 100% not to mention Wanyama & Alderweireld out so they'll be fine. Good to have the bragging rights for a while and it was a much needed win beyond the context of a derby.

          • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

            @MEHJones- He did ok considering this isn't a natural position for him given his skill set. There were a number of times where we closed down attacking passing avenues so he had to square it or pass backwards but there were also a couple of times where he could've been more progressive, be it passing or running with the ball, and he chose the conservative option. He is at his best as the right side of a front 3 where the choices he has to make are sometimes made up for him (I think decision making is his biggest weakness) but he did a job in this game. He should have more joy against Dortmund playing in a similar position- although I would guess Winks will play next to Dembele in that game so Spurs can control the ball if needed.
